latest_video_data.title: How to improve at Deadlock: Artificial Skill
latest_video_data.description:
After the last unedited video I was disappointed, so I wasted the rest of my time to make this.

Music by @bouncytorch (not sponsored)
All twitch/youtube references are in the video

My twitch: https://www.twitch.tv/mattia_json

0:00 The best
0:50 Artificial Skill
3:20 Part by Part Imitation
5:22 Mechanization by Iteration
7:19 Fearless Learning
8:12 Perfect Echo Chambers


#coaching #deadlock #tips #learning #selfimprovement #shortessay 




Here is the transcript of, well, the script that I could fit into the description.

Do you want to be the best?
Perhaps just hit your peak and then look back at it for the rest of your life
Or maybe you have someone to impress. Something to prove.



Today, I'll teach you how to get there.
Today, I'll teach you about Artificial Skill 
Mattia — 11/20/2025 1:54 PM
First off, we have to address the elephants in the room: Talent and Hard work.

Some people's previous experiences, or lack thereof make them more efficient at understanding where and how to put effort in whatever task they take on. Another part of talent resides in what makes one settle. Does he do too little and lacks care for the important parts of the skill, or does he perfectly understand when and where he should be good?
When you're comparing yourself with someone who "just gets it right" you'll end up in an abyss of misunderstanding. Why do we play the same amount of games but he's just better than me? How do I fill this gap?

Say hello to the other elephant: hard work.
You need to train harder!
You need to be there more than him!
You just need more time and work.

Oh you viewers have no idea how much I hate these statements. 
You will not get better than anyone by mindlessly doing more of what you're doing. You'll just find out if you're statistically in the group of people who can understand how to fix his mistakes and, basically, is a part of those talented individuals.

Drumrolls: It's time to talk about artificial skill.
DEFINITION:
Artificial Skill is a set of adjustments to a specific part of how you do something that you don't necessarily understand but makes you better than others at the same leve.

Artificial skill is the promise of every coaching video about anything you ever watched. The promise of every tip and trick. The ability to out-talent and out-work peers at your same skill level with the acquisition of information.

If you're still not the best player at every game you've ever watched a coaching video for, you may either think that those coaching videos were either bad or that coaching just doesn't work.

 Here it is, the secret formula to acquire infinite artificial skill:
Mattia — 11/20/2025 2:06 PM
Part by part imitation. 
Mechanization by iteration.
Fearless learning
Perfect Echo Chambers
Mattia — Yesterday at 3:49 PM
Part by part imitation
Have you ever sketched out something starting from a reference? A monster from a videogame when you were a kid, or perhaps the face of someone you liked. 
If someone hasn't told you already, let me be the first: The result of your imitation wasn't bad or good, it was a new piece of art. Your translation between what you saw, imagined, visualized, and what your hands did was a new unique image in the world. 
The good thing about imitating something is that you can decide both what your reference is and how close you want to go to it. 
Mattia — Yesterday at 3:57 PM
My personal approach to the subject is the following:
If you're clueless, copy everything.
If you think you're not clueless, copy every single detail about everything.
If you know what you want to learn, then look for that part.

What I found out when I first started playing paradox and thought I had her figured out was that the more I watched Tas or MikaelS play the more I found small things I could do differently. The more I found out things could have been done differently, the more I started looking for one small change at a time.

My tip is to look for someone who is widely considered the current best at doing what you're looking to improve on, and find small things he does differently from you. It can be timings, how he manages his hp, how aggressive he is, when he becomes aggressive, when he pushes, when does he fight and when does he flee.
How does he move? Which cooldowns does he use?

The goal is to acquire the target's sense of importance and execution for your own gameplay, all while getting a visible goal for improvement.
Mattia — Yesterday at 4:11 PM
While this first part is already enough for most people who are at or below the mean average of the skill level in a game to gain a noticeable improvement, the next ones are the de-facto necessity for speeding up the process.
